            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Baron Alexander von Humboldt.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>We have announced the death of the Prussian Mi-<lb
            break="no"/>nister William de Humboldt. The following particu-<lb break="no"/>lars of
          his last moments are from a letter written by<lb break="yes"/>his brother Alexander, the
          great traveller, to M.<lb break="yes"/>Arago, dated Tegel, near Berlin, the 10th
            instant:&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>&#x201C;I have lost my brother, who died the night
            before<lb break="yes"/>last. We had seen him gradually sinking for ten days.<lb
            break="yes"/>His weakness had been progressively increasing for<lb break="yes"/>several
          weeks, and his limbs became subject to a con-<lb break="no"/>stant trembling. Still his
          mind retained all its vigour.<lb break="yes"/>He never ceased his labours, and has left
          two works<lb break="yes"/>very nearly finished&#x2014;one in the languages of the In-<lb
            break="no"/>dian Archipelago as derived from the Sanscrit, and<lb break="yes"/>the other
          on the origin and philosophy of language in<lb break="yes"/>general. My brother has
          bequeathed his manuscripts<lb break="yes"/>and unfinished works, and his valuable
          collection of<lb break="yes"/>books, to the public library. He died of an inflamma-<lb
            break="no"/>tion of the chest, watching with painful sagacity the<lb break="yes"
          />progress of the disease. His understanding was of<lb break="yes"/>the highest order, and
          his soul filled with exalted and<lb break="yes"/>noble sentiments.&#x201D;&#x2014;<hi
            rendition="#i">Galignani&#x2019;s Messenger.</hi>
        </p>
            </div>
